==Chinese==
{{zh-forms|2=origin|lit=the sun's origin; where the sun originates}}
{{wp|zh:日本 (消歧義),yue:,lzh:,gan:,hak:,cdo:,nan:,wuu:}}

===Etymology===
From {{compound|ja|日|t1=sun|本|t2=origin, root}}.

{{box-top}}
As a state name, the term likely grew from a 7th‑century self‑conception in state letters and gradually replaced {{m|ja|倭}} in external usage. The earliest known epigraphic use of {{m|ja|日本}} appears in 678, but in a highly literary sense. Documentary records show an oscillation between {{m|ja|倭}} and {{m|ja|日本}} in the late 670s. By 702–703, the self‑designation {{m|ja|日本國}} was stable (Korean sources adopted {{m|ja|日本國}} from 698). Chinese histories (the ''{{w|New Book of Tang|Xin Tang Shu}}'' and ''{{w|Old Book of Tang|Jiu Tang Shu}}'') place the renaming around 670; the claim that “{{w|Wu Zetian}} changed it” is best interpreted as Tang-dynasty recognition of the new name.

Early diplomatic topos (607):
{{zh-x|日出 處 天子 致 書 日没 處 天子 無恙。|“The Son of Heaven from where the sun rises sends a letter to the Son of Heaven where the sun sets—may you be well.”|ref=隋書·東夷·倭國（607）|collapsed=y}}

Earliest epigraphic 日本 (often rhetorical; sometimes read as “Baekje”) (678):
{{zh-x|於 時 日本 餘噍，据 扶桑 以 逋誅。|“At that time the remnant of ‘Japan’ clung to Fusang to evade punishment.”|ref=大唐故右威衛將軍上柱國祢公墓誌銘|collapsed=y}}

Reports of renaming (670):
{{zh-x|倭國 更 號 日本，自 言 近 日 所 出 以 為 名。|“The country of Wa changed its name to ‘Japan’, saying it was so named because it lay near where the sun rises.”|ref=三國史記·新羅本紀·文武王十年|collapsed=y}}

Earliest possible documentary 日本 (if authentic), preserved via quotation (664):
{{zh-x|函 上 著 鎮西將軍 日本 鎮西 筑紫 大將軍 牒。|“On the case was written: ‘Memorandum of the West‑Pacifying General, the Grand General of Tsukushi of Japan.’”|ref=善鄰國寳記（15th c.）引《海外國記》|collapsed=y}}

Transition/oscillation in documents (671/672):
{{zh-x|書 曰：「大唐 帝 敬 問 日本國 天皇」；「大唐 皇帝 敬 問 倭 王 書」／「皇帝 敬 致 書 於 日本 國王」。|“(671) ‘The Great Tang Emperor respectfully inquires of the Heavenly Sovereign of the State of Japan’; (672) ‘The Emperor of Great Tang respectfully inquires of the King of Wa’ / ‘The Emperor respectfully addresses the King of the State of Japan’.”|ref=善鄰國寳記（15th c.）|collapsed=y}}

Stabilized self‑designation (702~703):
{{zh-x|有 人 來 問 曰：「何 處 使人？」答 曰：「日本國 使。」|“Someone asked, ‘Envoys from where?’ He replied, ‘Envoys of the State of Japan.’”|ref=續日本紀（702–703）|collapsed=y}}
{{box-bottom}}

