==Japanese==

===Etymology 1===
{{ja-kanjitab|に|ほん|yomi=nanori,goon}}
{{wp|ja:}}
{{wp|Names of Japan}}

{{IPAchar|/nitɨpoɴ/}} → {{IPAchar|/nip̚poɴ/}} → {{IPAchar|/niɸoɴ/}} → {{IPAchar|/nihoɴ/}}

Coined in Japan of [[Sinic]] elements, as compound of {{com|ja|日|tr1=nichi|t1=[[sun]]|本|tr2=hon|t2=[[origin]]}} and literally meaning "origin of the sun". The ''hon'' element was apparently pronounced {{IPAchar|/poɴ/}} when first coined. Over time, the initial {{IPAchar|/p/}} [[lenition|lenited]], becoming {{IPAchar|/ɸ/}} as shown in the ''Nifon'' entry in the 1603 ''Nippo Jisho'' ("Japanese-Portuguese Dictionary").<ref name="NPJ">{{R:Nippo Jisho}}</ref> This then became the {{IPAchar|/h/}} sound in modern Japanese.<ref name="NKDc">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten Concise}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref>

{{box-top}}
In older texts, this was read as ''{{ll|ja|訓読み|kun'yomi}}'' as {{m|ja|日の本|tr=Hinomoto}}. The ''{{ll|ja|音読み|on'yomi}}'' readings ''Nippon'' and ''Nihon'' became more common in the {{w|Heian period}}, with both persisting into modern use.<ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref> The ''Nihon'' reading appears to be the most common in everyday Japanese usage.<ref>'''2012''', {{lang|ja|[http://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXBZO37629750Y1A221C1000000/ ニホンVSニッポン 「日本」の読み方、どっちが優勢?]}}, ''[[w:The Nikkei|The Nikkei]]''</ref>

This [[appellation]] comes from {{w|Prince Shōtoku}}'s famous letter from {{w|Prince Shōtoku}} to {{w|Emperor Yang of Sui}} sent via the {{w|Japanese missions to Sui China|Japanese mission to Sui China in 607}}, wherein we see the first mention of Japan as the {{m|en|Land of the Rising Sun}}, and a description of China as ''Land of the Setting Sun'':
: {{zh-x|日 出 處 天子 致書 日 沒 處 天子 無恙 云云|...the son of heaven of the land of the rising sun sends a letter to the son of heaven of the place where the sun sets, for good health and so on.|CL|collapsed=y|nocat=y}}

{{zh-m|[[日]][[出]][[處]]|lit=[[sun]] + [[emerge]] + [[place]]}} here refers to Japan, while {{zh-m|[[日]][[沒]][[處]]|lit=sun + [[sink#Verb|sink]] + place}} refers to [[China]].  "Sun emerge place" both refers to the [[eastward]] [[position]] of Japan relative to China, and metaphorically places the Yamato Kingship during Empress Suiko's reign on a similar footing as to the Sui dynasty under Emperor Yang's rule.

The earliest date for the specific spelling {{m|ja||日本|lit=sun source}} instead of the periphrastic {{zh-m|[[日]][[出]][[處]]|lit=sun emerge place}} may be 664, as mentioned in a  fragment of the 733 text {{m|ja||海外国記|tr=Kaigai Kokki|Record of Overseas Countries}}, describing a letter given in 664 to a Tang emissary arriving in {{w|Dazaifu (government)|Dazaifu}}.<ref name="N">{{R:Nipponica}}</ref>  However, it remains an open question whether this instance of {{m|ja||日本}} might have been a change in name that happened between the actual event in 664 and the recording of that event in 733.<ref name="N"/>  More certainly, the Japanese source ''{{w|Shoku Nihongi}}'' relates that a 702 or 703 mission from Japan to the Tang court requested that the Chinese change the official name from {{m|ja|倭|tr=Wa}} to {{m|ja||日本|tr=Nippon}}, and this appears to be corroborated by accounts in the Chinese source ''{{w|Old Book of Tang}}''.<ref name="N"/><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=krq5CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA140 |title=The Cultural Dimensions of Sino-Japanese Relations: Essays on the Nineteenth and Twentieth Centuries |first= Joshua A. |last=Fogel |date=29 April 2015 |page=140 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1317457671 }}</ref>

Despite the spelling, the term may have been read out as the older name ''Yamato'' for some time afterwards, as suggested by kana glosses in sources such as the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'' poetry anthology of 759.<ref name="NKDc"/><ref name="MYS">{{RQ:MYS|1|63}}</ref>
{{box-bottom}}

