===Etymology 3===
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=kanon|じつ|k1=じっ|ほん|k2=ぽん}}

&#42;{{IPAchar|/zitʉpon/}} → {{IPAchar|/zip̚pon/}} → {{IPAchar|/ʑip̚pon/}}

Uses the ''[[漢音#Japanese|kan'on]]'' reading ''jitsu'' for {{l|ja|日}}, as compared to the ''[[呉音#Japanese|goon]]'' reading ''nichi''. First appears in texts from the early 1600s,<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref> notably the 1603 Japanese-Portuguese dictionary ''{{w|Nippo Jisho}}''. Probably influenced by European-language terminology for the country,<ref name="KDJ"/><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref> such as {{cog|pt|Japão}} or {{cog|nl|Japan}}, in turn arising from {{cog|nan-hbl|日本|tr=Ji̍t-pún}} via {{cog|ms|Jepun}}, or from {{cog|nan-tws|日本}} via {{cog|id|-}} {{cog|ms|Jepang}}.

====Pronunciation====
{{ja-pron|acc=3|じっぽん}}

====Proper noun====
{{ja-pos|proper|じっぽん}}

# {{lb|ja|sort=しっぽん'|archaic}} [[Japan]]
#* {{RQ:Nippo Jisho|365|passage='''Iippon''' {{lang|ja|ジッポン (日本)}} Fino moto. {{lang|ja|(日の本) 東洋. すなわち、日本.}}}}
#* ['''Note:'''The quoted ''ii'' in ''iippon'' is the 16th century Portuguese romanization representing ji, pronounced *[ʒi] in Portuguese, since i and j weren't consistently distinguished orthographically.]

